John Edward: Language skills are a must for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have a number of academic successes behind them and it continues in 2018 with other excellent test results. Individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community activities only underline this.
The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) represents the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (Scotland) and strives to provide the best level of service to its students and parents.
Independent schools prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can design and implement individually tailored school education plans, we observe that modern languages are still popular and sought-after subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes straight to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.”
It is an important point of view that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely solely on English.
The latest results of this year’s tests show that languages are at the top of the charts, with the highest success rates being offered by independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned a foreign language achieved the best grades of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that the highest mark A reached 72 percent of students of Mandarin, 72 percent of students of German, 69 percent of students of French and 63 percent of students of Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects that students choose are equally valued as STEM subjects (science, technology, technical fields and mathematics) in the study plans of independent and other schools.
A survey conducted by the British Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 showed that, for reasons that employers cite as problems when occupying vacancies, 17 per cent of the workforce is under-represented in language skills.
That is why language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job opportunities require languages, these skills are a necessity in the globalized world.
Whether a man chooses any career, if he has learned a second language, he will have the real advantage in the future, that he has such lifelong skills.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages automatically gains an advantage over competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to lead a conversation, with the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people, 15 percent being French.
That is why it is important for today’s children to invest in language teaching.
If children know more languages, especially those of developing economies, they will have a greater chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, every school is different from the language it teaches.
Many schools focus on more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be most important for the UK in the outlook for 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whether the child is interested in anything, he will always have in independent schools a choice of several languages with teachers who are experts in the given field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
At this point, it cannot be denied that languages are essential in the global business environment for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should, in fact, be regarded as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, variety and attraction to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
